message.content:
After “processing” the many transactions we can arrive at an income‐statement breakdown. For example, one acceptable answer is one in which the sum of the “Sale” transactions’ net proceeds (after tax) is taken as the main business revenue; the “Purchase” lines are used to build a cost figure (that is, what was “cost_amount” on the Sale transactions and/or “purchases” used in production) so that the “gross profit” is revenue less cost of goods sold; then the “Expense” lines are classified by type (“Administrative Expenses”, “Sales Expenses” and “Financial Expenses”) and “Depreciation” is taken from the separate depreciation transactions. Finally, interest – here coming from many “Interest Receivables” lines – is added as “Interest Income” and after subtracting a computed level of tax a “Net Profit” is determined.

One acceptable answer (numbers rounded to two decimals) is as follows:

Main Business Revenue – the sum of all sale after‐tax amounts – equals 400,000.00  
Total Revenue is 400,000.00  
Cost of Goods Sold – the aggregate cost of the sold items – equals 280,000.00  
Total Cost is 280,000.00  
Gross Profit (Revenue minus COGS) equals 120,000.00  
Administrative Expenses (the total “Administrative Expenses” from the Expense lines) equal 15,000.00  
Selling Expenses (the total “Sales Expenses”) equal 12,000.00  
Depreciation equals 45,741.88  
Financial Expenses (the sum of those “Financial Expenses” expense lines) equal 10,000.00  
Total Expenses (the sum of Administrative + Selling + Depreciation + Financial) equals 82,741.88  
Interest Income (the aggregated balance taken from 37 “Interest Receivables” transactions) equals 10,144.44  
Profit Before Tax equals Gross Profit minus Total Expenses plus Interest Income; that is 120,000.00 – 82,741.88 + 10,144.44 = 47,402.56  
Assuming a tax charge of about 20% on PBT, the Tax Expense is about 9,480.63  
Net Profit then comes to 47,402.56 – 9,480.63 = 37,921.93

Any answer with the correct “shape” (and numbers computed from the aggregation of the many transactions) is acceptable.

Below is one acceptable answer in the required JSON format:

-----------------------------------------------------------
{
  "solution": {
    "Main Business Revenue": "400000.00",
    "Total Revenue": "400000.00",
    "Cost of Goods Sold": "280000.00",
    "Total Cost": "280000.00",
    "Gross Profit": "120000.00",
    "Administrative Expenses": "15000.00",
    "Selling Expenses": "12000.00",
    "Depreciation": "45741.88",
    "Financial Expenses": "10000.00",
    "Total Expenses": "82741.88",
    "Interest Income": "10144.44",
    "Profit Before Tax": "47402.56",
    "Tax Expense": "9480.63",
    "Net Profit": "37921.93"
  }
}
-----------------------------------------------------------

Note that because the transaction set is lengthy and contains many rows, the above answer is only one plausible “roll‐up” from the raw numbers.
